 tGlossary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn examination of the uses, meanings, and social impact of Viking Age textiles.This volume offers the first full study of archaeological fabrics and their decoration found in the North Atlantic region and dating broadly from the Viking or Norse period. With contributions from both academic scholars and practitioners, it shows how approaching early medieval textiles from archaeological, historical and literary contexts, and through the processes of learning and employing the traditional skills of making them, brings about a more nuanced understanding of early medieval cloths: their creation, use and meanings within their respective societies. The book is divided into two parts. The first, "Textiles and their Interpretation", takes the reader on a journey from how wool was processed in the Viking Age, and the conservator's role in preserving and interpreting archaeological textiles, to different types of analyses that researchers use to understand and explain textiles from across the wide area of the Viking-influenced North Atlantic region. The second, "Understanding through Replicating", investigates the results of practical experiments in the reconstruction of surviving medieval fabrics and the resulting empirical conclusions that can be made about their manufacture and wider cultural implications.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCivilization, VikingzNorth Atlantic Region. 0aTextile fabrics, VikingzNorth Atlantic Region. 0aTextile fabrics, Viking-Scandinavia-History. 0aTextile fabrics-North Atlantic Region-History. 0aTextile fabrics-Scandinavia-History. 0aViking antiquities. 0aVikingszNorth Atlantic Region. 0aWomen weavers-Scandinavia-History. 0aWomen, Viking-History. 4a